{{Zoroastrianism}}
'''Exegesis in Zoroastrianism''' is principally defined as the interpretation of [[Avesta]], the Zoroastrian religious book. The [[Zend]], an explanation of Avesta which is written in [[middle Persian|Pahlavi language]] and the other old texts related to [[Zoroastrian]] exegesis have no [[Avestan language|Avestan]] word. The religious legal textbooks like [[Vendidad]], [[Neyrangistan, Hirbodistan, Hadokht Nask]] and [[Visperad]] are also interpretations of Avesta.<ref name="Thes">{{Cite thesis |last=Shapira |first=Dan |title=Studies in Zoroastrian Exegesis - Zand  |degree=PhD |url=https://archive.org/details/StudiesInZoroastrianExegesis-Zand |language=English}}</ref><ref name="Shz">{{Cite journal |last=Hashemi |first=Mahsa |last2=Najari |first2=Hossein | title=Avestan Architecture: A Descriptive Etymological Lexicon |url=https://www.scipress.com/ILSHS.63.59 |journal=International Letters of Social and Humanistic Sciences |publisher=SciPress Ltd., |publication-place=Switzerland |publication-date=2015 |volume=63 |pages=105–116 |doi=10.18052/www.scipress.com/ILSHS.63.105}}</ref>

