{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{BLP sources|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox chef | name = Lorraine Pascale | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|11|17}} | birth_place = [[London]], [[England]] | death_date = | death_place = | spouse = {{marriage|Count Kazimierz Balinski-Jundzill|1995|2000|reason=div}} | children = [[Ella Balinska]] | style = | education = | ratings = <!-- {{plainlist| }} --> | restaurants = | prevrests = <!-- {{plainlist| }} --> | television = {{plainlist| * ''Baking Made Easy'' * ''[[Donut Showdown]]'' * ''[[Halloween Baking Championship]]'' * ''[[Holiday Baking Championship]]'' * ''Home Cooking Made Easy'' * ''How to Be a Better Cook'' * ''Lorraine's Fast, Fresh & Easy Food'' * ''Lorraine's Last Minute Christmas'' * ''[[My Kitchen Rules with Niels (UK TV series)|My Kitchen Rules]]'' * ''[[Spring Baking Championship]]'' * ''Sugar Showdown'' * ''[[Worst Bakers in America]]''}} | awards = <!-- {{plainlist| }} --> | website = {{url|http://www.lorrainepascale.com}} }}
'''Lorraine Pascale''' (born 17 November 1972) is an English television cook and former model, best known for selling almost one million books in the UK alone. She has presented three television series for the [[BBC]] and has opened her own retail outlet in London selling baked goods.
==Personal life== Pascale was born to [[Afro-Caribbean|African-Caribbean]] parents<ref name=gua/> in [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]] at The Mothers' Hospital and was fostered shortly after she was born.<ref>''Fostering and Me with Lorraine Pascale.'' BBC documentary. (Shown on BBC2 on 19 June 2014.)</ref> She was [[adoption|adopted]] at 18 months old and brought up in [[Oxfordshire]] by an ethnically English family. When her adoptive parents divorced when she was three years old, Pascale remained with her mother, who subsequently became ill. At this point, at age seven, she was [[Foster care|fostered]] to more than one family, with differing degrees of 'fit'. Eventually she returned to her mother. She won a full scholarship given by the [[Buttle UK|Buttle Trust]] and so was educated at a [[boarding school]] in Devon.<ref name=gua>{{cite web | last=McGrath | first=Nick | title=Lorraine Pascale: My family values | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=22 January 2011 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/jan/22/lorraine-pascal-baking-cakes | accessdate=22 January 2011 }}</ref>
Pascale has an elder adoptive brother and a half-sister (her adoptive father had a daughter after the divorce). She knows her biological parents' identity and their four other children, but she does not wish to re-establish contact.<ref name=gua />
Pascale was married to Polish musician Count Kazimierz Balinski-Jundzill and the couple had a daughter, actress [[Ella Balinska]]. The couple separated in 2000 and subsequently divorced.<ref name=gua /><ref>{{cite web | last=Dunbar | first=Polly | title=From the catwalk to TV's Queen of Cakes: Lorraine Pascale tells her inspiring story | work=Daily Mail | date=14 February 2011 | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-1356398/From-catwalk-TVs-Queen-Cakes-Lorraine-Pascale-tells-inspiring-story.html | accessdate=8 October 2013 }}</ref>
==Career== At age 16, Pascale was spotted as potential model by the agent who had found [[Naomi Campbell]].<ref name=fmd>{{cite web | last= | first= | title=Lorraine Pascale | work=[[Fashion Model Directory]] | date=2 January 2011 | url=http://www.fashionmodeldirectory.com/models/Lorraine_Pascale/| accessdate=22 January 2011 }}</ref> Based in New York, she achieved recognition as the first black British model to appear on the cover of American ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''.<ref name=obs>{{cite web | last=Cooke | first=Rachel | title=Lorraine Pascale: 'I absolutely eat what I cook' | work=[[The Observer]] | date=2 January 2011 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/jan/02/lorraine-pascale-ellas-bakery-cupcakes | accessdate=22 January 2011 }}</ref> She appeared in the 1998 [[Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issue|''Sports Illustrated'' swimsuit issue]],<ref name="sportsillustrated">{{cite web |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/swimsuit/modelfeatured/lorraine_pascale/1998/model/1/5/index.htm |title=Swimsuit collection – Lorraine Pascale |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher=[[Time Warner]] |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> and featured as one of the '[[Bond Girls]]' in [[Robbie Williams]] "[[Millennium (song)|Millennium]]" video.<ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/baking-hot-with-new-bbc-chef-lorraine-pascale-6566152.html Baking hot with new BBC chef, Lorraine Pascale]</ref>
Pascale recognised the need to ensure her future after modelling and embarked on a series of career "try-outs", including [[hypnotherapy]] and [[car mechanic]]s. She took a diploma cookery course at Leith's School of Food and Wine in 2005 and found that cookery fitted her "like a pair of old jeans". After gaining her diploma, she did a series of 'stages' in some London restaurants but, realising that restaurant hours would not suit her, Pascale established herself as a specialist cakemaker, with a contract with [[Selfridges]]. Her introduction to Selfridges was at the suggestion of chef [[Marco Pierre White]] and in 2008 and 2010 she supplied the London store with over 1000 Christmas cakes. Pascale has opened her own cupcake shop in [[Covent Garden]]. She also studied Culinary Arts at Thames Valley University (now [[University of West London]]) and in March 2012 graduated with a first class degree.<ref name=obs /><ref name=obsa>{{cite web | last=Vernon | first=Polly | title=The model baker | work=[[The Observer]] | date=24 May 2009 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/may/24/lorraine-pascale-model-baker | accessdate=22 January 2011 }}</ref>
In 2015, Pascale said she practises [[Transcendental Meditation technique|Transcendental Meditation]] to relax after work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fitspiration – Lorraine Pascale|url=http://hipandhealthy.com/fitspiration-lorraine-pascale/|website=Hip & Healthy|accessdate=28 August 2015|date=5 March 2015|quote=To unwind after a busy day I practise transcendental meditation which I do morning and evening for 20 minutes each time. ... The meditation keeps me grounded, learn to be honest with myself, and only do the things which I feel will make me happy.}}</ref>
===Television and publishing work=== In January 2011, Pascale presented a television bakery programme in 2011, ''Baking Made Easy'', on [[BBC]] television<ref name=obs /> and published a bakery book based upon this series. Later that year, a second series, ''Home Cooking Made Easy'', was broadcast in September and October, with an accompanying book. A ''Last Minute Christmas'' programme aired on BBC Two on 22 December 2011. A third book was published in 2012 and a series based upon it, called ''Fast, Fresh & Easy Food'', aired in August and September 2012 on [[BBC Two]].
Since January 2014, Pascale co-presents and judges the UK version of ''[[My Kitchen Rules (UK TV series)|My Kitchen Rules]]'' with [[Jason Atherton]] on [[Sky Living]]. In early 2014, it was announced that Pascale was to host a new six-part television series called ''Lorraine Pascale: How to be a Better Cook'' that would air later in the year on [[BBC Two]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atvtoday.co.uk/54372-bbc/ |title=Lorraine Pascale gives novice cooks a helping hand in BBC Two factual series |publisher=ATV Today |date=7 April 2014}}</ref> In March 2015, she co-hosted ''The Nation's Favourite Food'' alongside [[the Hairy Bikers]]. The show aired for one episode on BBC Two.
Lorraine is also a judge on [[Food Network]]'s ''[[Holiday Baking Championship]]'' and ''[[Spring Baking Championship]]'' as well as a mentor on ''[[Worst Bakers in America]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/hosts/lorraine-pascale/bio.html?oc=linkback|title=Lorraine Pascale Bio : Food Network|website=www.foodnetwork.com|access-date=2016-05-09}}</ref> She was a judge in a few episodes of the first season of ''Bakers Vs Fakers'', and became the hostess for Season 2.
==Charity== Pascale is the patron of [[The Adolescent and Children's Trust|TACT]], the UK's largest fostering and adoption charity, and an ambassador of both the charities [https://www.raysofsunshine.org.uk/ Rays of Sunshine] and [[The Prince's Trust]]. In summer 2012, she was made the ambassador of the [[National Careers Service]] launching the service with Skills Minister [[John Hayes (British politician)|John Hayes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skillsfundingagency.bis.gov.uk/news/pressreleases/TV-Chef-Lorraine-Pascale-and-Minister-John-Hayes-launch-National--Careers-Service.htm |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140108013054/http://www.skillsfundingagency.bis.gov.uk/news/pressreleases/TV-Chef-Lorraine-Pascale-and-Minister-John-Hayes-launch-National--Careers-Service.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2014-01-08 |title=TV Chef Lorraine Pascale and Minister John Hayes launch National Careers Service}}</ref> Pascale also visits schools to talk to children and young adults, spreading positivity and motivation.
