'''C. René Padilla''' (born 1932) is an [[Ecuadorians|Ecuadorian]] [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] [[Theology|theologian]] and [[Missiology|missiologist]] known for coining the term ''[[integral mission]]'' ({{Lang-es|misión integral}}) in the 1970s to articulate Christianity's dual priority in evangelism and social activism. He would popularize this term in Latin American evangelicalism through the [[Latin American Theological Fellowship]] and through global evangelicalism through the [[First International Congress on World Evangelization|Lausanne Conference]] of 1974.
== Life == Padilla was born into a poor family in [[Quito]], [[Ecuador]], in 1932. Due to the [[Great Depression]], his family would move when he was two years old to [[Colombia]], where he would grow up.<ref name="Marks2008" /> He would later pursue a BA in philosophy and a MA in theology at [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]], before continuing on to complete a PhD in the New Testament from the [[University of Manchester]], under [[F. F. Bruce]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theworkofthepeople.com/person/rene-padilla|title=René Padilla|last=|first=|date=|website=The Work Of The People|publisher=|access-date=30 November 2016}}</ref>
His education and experiences with [[InterVarsity Christian Fellowship]] underscored Padilla's evangelical foundations and the priority he would place on the [[Historical criticism|historical-critical approach]] to [[Biblical hermeneutics|hermeneutics]].<ref name="Marks2008">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LjnJCnZQwY0C&pg=PA127|title=Shaping a Global Theological Mind|last=Padilla|first=C. René|publisher=Ashgate Publishing|year=2008|isbn=978-0-7546-9253-9|editor-last=Marks|editor-first=Darren C.|location=Aldershot, England|pages=127–138|chapter=My Theological Pilgrimage}}</ref> However, in 1959, Padilla was appointed a traveling secretary in Latin America for [[International Fellowship of Evangelical Students]]. In his work with universities throughout Venezuela, Colombia, Peru, and Ecuador, Padilla would be faced with a tense sociopolitical context. Students were immersed in Marxist writings and grappled with the possibility of revolution. This would be the context which produced not only [[Liberation theology#Latin American liberation theology|Catholic liberation theology]], but also challenged Padilla to develop a new evangelical social theology which he would later term "[[integral mission]]."<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kirkpatrick|first=David C.|date=April 2016|year=|title=C. René Padilla and the Origins of Integral Mission in Post-War Latin America|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-ecclesiastical-history/article/c-rene-padilla-and-the-origins-of-integral-mission-in-post-war-latin-america/0566D6A9D1D180A4F9FCC89340774E30|journal=The Journal of Ecclesiastical History|volume=67|issue=2|pages=351–371|doi=10.1017/S0022046915001670|issn=0022-0469|via=}}</ref>
Padilla would bring his ideas to the global stage at the [[First International Congress on World Evangelization|Lausanne Conference]] of 1974.<ref name="GreenmanGreen2012">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TxdsAQgn9z8C&pg=PA74|title=Global Theology in Evangelical Perspective: Exploring the Contextual Nature of Theology and Mission|last=Escobar|first=Samuel|publisher=InterVarsity Press|others=Gene L. Green|year=2012|isbn=978-0-8308-6970-1|location=Downers Grove, Illinois|pages=74ff|chapter=Doing Theology on Christ's Road|editor=Jeffrey P. Greenman}}</ref> This would have a significant effect on the nature of global evangelicalism and the growing priority of evangelicals in both evangelicalism and social activism.<ref name="Stanley2013">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UMhsoyVuefIC&pg=PA151|title=The Global Diffusion of Evangelicalism: The Age of Billy Graham and John Stott|last=Stanley|first=Brian|publisher=InterVarsity Press|year=2013|isbn=978-0-8308-2585-1|location=Downers Grove, Illinois|pages=151–180}}</ref>
In 1992, Padilla would receive an honorary [[Doctor of Divinity]] degree from Wheaton College.<ref name=":0" />
He is the father of the theologian [[Ruth Padilla DeBorst]].
== Works == * {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7X2UPpL23qAC|title=Mission Between the Times: Essays on the Kingdom|edition=rev.|last=Padilla|first=C. René|publisher=Langham Monographs|location=Carlisle|year=2010|isbn=978-1-907713-01-9}}
